oovy code to test triggering closure43.class$ via Groovy’s MetaClass? There are some complexities here!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring test improvements**\\n\\nI'm considering whether we can enhance the test by accessing closure43 through the public API and removing direct helpers since that feels like a violation. However, the user wants the remaining sections left uncovered. If we could generate a dynamic access report that states \\\"method was reached if any non-synthetic line covered,\\\" that could help. I'm questioning why closure's class$ shows false coverage, potentially because it hasn’t been reached properly. If we can invoke it through reflection, will it then be included in the JaCoCo report?\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Investigating JaCoCo instrumentation**\\n\\nIt seems the report relies on a native agent, which makes me wonder if dependencies are only instrumented when accessed through the public API and not when loaded directly by the class loader. Could I test this in Java with Class.forName to access closure43 and then use reflection? However, since the target call site is within the closure class, I might run into coverage issues. I’m considering using Groovy's MetaClass to invoke the static method instead, even though that might be challenging too.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering class loading mechanics**\\n\\nI’m thinking about the absence of Class.forName and inspecting how dynamic access works. It’s likely using generated native config reports, depending on the callsite for metadata. For RestAssured, it seems no new metadata is created since it’s statically initialized. I wonder if I should select a public class or perhaps use a class helper for loading. Maybe I need to make the target specific and ensure I'm only dealing with the active class.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_JlrDoEKQOZzqulYZPkjKNCed|fc_0d7a0cc05462283e016a276380ddcc81939bf1258aae240115", "name": "read", "ar